  "slug": "body-scan-for-sleep",
  "title": "Body scan for sleep",
  "subtitle": "A body scan from soles to crown, used as a wind-down rather than a sleep technique.",
  "excerpt": "A guided body scan from the soles of the feet to the top of the head, used in bed as the last ten or fifteen minutes before sleep. Falling asleep mid-scan is the intended use.",
  "type": "PRACTICE",
  "sourceNotes": "Body scan meditation: public-domain lineage, secular MBSR adaptation by Jon Kabat-Zinn at UMass, late 1970s. Bedtime framing contributed by Rebecca Page, from Day 3 of SLEEP: A 30-Day Tapping Intensive (2025, ISBN 9798269649795).",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A guided body scan from the soles of the feet to the top of the head, used in bed as the last ten or fifteen minutes before sleep. Attention moves slowly through the body, one region at a time. Most people fall asleep mid-scan; that's the intended use.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "New to body-based meditation? Read ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "body-based meditation",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "link",
                "attrs": {
                  "href": "/mindset/body-based-meditation"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " first.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The practice",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Setting up",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Lie down in bed, on your back. A pillow under the knees if your lower back is tender. Arms by your sides, palms up. Eyes closed.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Three slow breaths. Inhale through the nose, exhale through the mouth.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The scan",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bring your attention to the soles of your feet. Notice what's there, warmth, coolness, pressure against the sheet. Don't try to change anything. Two breaths.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Move up through the body, two breaths at each region:",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "the tops of the feet, the ankles",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "the calves, behind the knees",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "the thighs",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "the hips, the lower back",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "the belly, rising and falling with the breath",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "the chest, rising and falling with the breath",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "the fingertips, the hands, the wrists",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "the forearms, the elbows, the upper arms",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "the shoulders",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "the neck, the back of the head",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "the jaw, the cheeks, the small muscles around the eyes",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "the forehead, the top of the head",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "When the attention wanders, notice that it has wandered. Bring it back to the region you were on.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Coming back",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "If you've reached the top of the head and you're still awake, rest the attention on the whole body for a few breaths. Lengthen each exhale: in for four, out for six. Then four, out for seven. Then four, out for eight.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "How it adapts",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Sitting at a desk rather than in bed: shorten to five minutes and stop at the shoulders. The scan still resets the nervous system; the bedtime extension into the head and jaw is for the wind-down.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Restless legs or chronic ankle pain: start at the belly and move up, then come back to the legs at the end. Some people find the leg regions easier to hold last rather than first.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Too tired to follow the order: rest the attention on whichever region holds tension, usually the jaw, shoulders, or belly. Two breaths there, then let go. The whole-body order is the standard; an attention-to-one-region version is the short fallback.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Awake at 3am: the same scan works in the middle of the night. Falling asleep again mid-scan is the intended use here too.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this practice comes from",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Body scan meditation has roots in several contemplative traditions. The form used here is the secular MBSR adaptation developed by Jon Kabat-Zinn at the University of Massachusetts in the late 1970s. The bedtime framing, where the body scan is a sleep wind-down rather than a daytime sit, was contributed by Rebecca Page from Day 3 of SLEEP: A 30-Day Tapping Intensive. See the sources note for the publication detail.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
